1. cs.NA (Numerical Analysis): The paper presents a parallel algorithm for radial basis function interpolation that uses an iterative solver and a fast matrix-vector algorithm. This falls under the domain of numerical analysis, making cs.NA the most likely sub-category. 

2. cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing): The paper focuses on developing a parallel algorithm that scales well up to a thousand processes. This falls under the domain of distributed and parallel computing, making cs.DC a likely sub-category. 

3. cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science): The paper discusses the use of radial basis function interpolation in particle methods for fluid simulation, which falls under the domain of computational engineering. This makes cs.CE a likely sub-category. 

4. cs.MS (Mathematical Software): The paper discusses the implementation of the algorithm using the petsc library, which is a software library for numerical computations. This makes cs.MS a possible sub-category. 

5. cs.SC (Symbolic Computation and Formal Languages): The paper does not focus on symbolic computation or formal languages, but it is possible that some aspects of the algorithm may fall under this sub-category. Hence, cs.SC is a less likely sub-category.
